{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17489778","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17489778"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:42+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T04:29:42+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"743"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/743"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.42,0.31,0.03,0.12]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104429"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"743","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/743"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"743"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86754"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"3696"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"4964"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18184"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36998"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43813"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104429","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/104429"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA previously well 23-year-old man presents with a one month history of abdominal pain, diarrhoea and weight loss. He drinks three cans of beer a day and does not smoke. Initial bloods reveal microcytic anaemia and C-reactive protein (CRP) of 45 mg/L (\u0026lt;5 mg/L). Faecal calprotectin is elevated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIleocolonoscopy reveals discontinuous lesions with a cobblestone appearance, with highest concentration in the transverse colon. There is no obvious ileal or rectal involvement. Histology reveals transmural inflammation and the patient is diagnosed with Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following factors is most indicative of a high risk of progressive disease?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["His alcohol consumption","The colonoscopy findings","His age","Non-smoking history","The CRP value"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EAt the time of diagnosis with Crohn\u0027s disease, the presence of specific features suggests an increased risk of disabling disease in the subsequent years. These include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAge \u0026lt; 40 years\u003C/strong\u003E\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETobacco use\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELow socioeconomic status\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIleocolonic disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERectal involvement\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGlucocorticoid-requiring disease\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe one risk factor that this 23-year-old has is his age. While smoking is \u003Cem\u003Eprotective\u003C/em\u003E in ulcerative colitis, it is a poor prognostic factor in Crohn\u0027s disease. For this and many other reasons, it is important that this patient continues to not smoke. Alcohol consumption is not a risk factor.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERaised CRP and transmural inflammation are typical characteristics of Crohn\u0027s disease and by themselves are not considered prognostic risk factors. A colonoscopic finding of rectal involvement might be an indicator of progressive disease, but that is not the case here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Young patients with Crohn\u0027s disease have a high risk of progressive disease."],"references":["Torres J, Mehandru S, Colombel J-F, et al. Crohn\u0027s disease. Lancet. 2017;389(10080):1741\u201355. Available at: https://doi.org/10.1016/S0140-6736(16)31711-1","Picco M. Risk factors associated with progression to intestinal complications of Crohn\u0027s disease in a population-based cohort. Yearbook of Gastroenterology. 2011;2011:152\u20133."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86754"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"743"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86754"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-06-02T08:43:20+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-06-02T08:44:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"743"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"104429"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree